.TH "HTMLSCRIPTELEMENT.SRC" "3JS" "January 6, 2026" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
HTMLScriptElement.src \- HTMLScriptElement: src property
.SH SYNOPSIS
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Warning:\f[R] This property represents the URI of an external
script loaded into the script element, which may be executable depending
on the script \f[CR]type\f[R].
APIs like this are known as injection sinks, and are potentially a
vector for cross\-site scripting (XSS) attacks.
.PP
You can mitigate this risk by having a Content Security Policy (CSP)
that restricts the locations from which scripts can be loaded, and by
always assigning \f[CR]TrustedScriptURL\f[R] objects instead of strings
and enforcing trusted types.
See Security considerations for more information.
.RE
.PP
The \f[B]\f[CB]src\f[B]\f[R] property of the
\f[CR]HTMLScriptElement\f[R] interface is a string representing the URL
of an external script; this can be used as an alternative to embedding a
script directly within a document.
.PP
It reflects the \f[CR]src\f[R] attribute of the \f[CR]<script>\f[R]
element.
.SH VALUE
Getting the property returns a string containing the element\(cqs script
URI.
.PP
Setting the property accepts either a \f[CR]TrustedScriptURL\f[R] object
or a string.
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]TypeError\f[R]
Thrown if the property is set with a string when Trusted Types are
enforced by a CSP and no default policy is defined.
This is also thrown if the fetched URL cannot be successfully parsed as
its indicated type, such as a module or importmap.
.SH DESCRIPTION
The \f[B]\f[CB]src\f[B]\f[R] property represents the URL of an external
script.
If set, scripts provided via the text properties \f[CR]text\f[R],
\f[CR]textContent\f[R], or \f[CR]innerText\f[R], are ignored.
.SS Security considerations
The \f[CR]src\f[R] property is used to load and run external scripts.
The fetched script is run in the context of the current page, and can
hence do anything that your own website code can do (even if the URL is
not same\-origin with your site).
If the input is provided by a user, this is a possible vector for
cross\-site scripting (XSS) attacks.
.PP
It is extremely risky to accept and execute arbitrary URLs from
untrusted origins.
A website should control what scripts that are allowed to run using a
Content Security Policy (CSP) with the \f[CR]script\-src\f[R] directive
(or a fallback defined in \f[CR]default\-src\f[R]).
This can restrict scripts to those from the current origin, or a
specific set of origins, or even particular files.
.PP
If you\(cqre using this property and enforcing trusted types (using the
\f[CR]require\-trusted\-types\-for\f[R] CSP directive), you will need to
always assign \f[CR]TrustedScriptURL\f[R] objects instead of strings.
This ensures that the input is passed through a transformation function,
which has the chance to reject or modify the URL before it is injected.
.PP
Even if the resource is trusted by your website, it may still be
compromised in a supply chain attack.
To mitigate against this kind of attack you should use the subresource
integrity feature.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Using TrustedScriptURL
To mitigate the risk of XSS, we should always assign
\f[CR]TrustedScriptURL\f[R] instances to the \f[CR]src\f[R] property.
We also need to do this if we\(cqre enforcing trusted types for other
reasons and we want to allow some script sources that have been
permitted (by \f[CR]CSP: script\-src\f[R]).
.PP
Trusted types are not yet supported on all browsers, so first we define
the trusted types tinyfill.
This acts as a transparent replacement for the trusted types JavaScript
API:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]if\f[R] (\f[B]typeof\f[R] trustedTypes === \(dqundefined\(dq)
  trustedTypes = { createPolicy: (n, rules) \f[B]=>\f[R] rules };
.EE
.PP
Next we create a \f[CR]TrustedTypePolicy\f[R] that defines a
\f[CR]createScriptURL()\f[R] method for transforming input strings into
\f[CR]TrustedScriptURL\f[R] instances.
.PP
For the purpose of this example we\(cqll assume that we want to allow a
predefined set of URLs in the \f[CR]scriptAllowList\f[R] array and log
any other scripts.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] scriptAllowList = [
  \f[I]// Some list of allowed URLs\f[R]
];
\f[B]const\f[R] policy = trustedTypes.createPolicy(\(dqscript\-url\-policy\(dq, {
  createScriptURL(input) {
    \f[B]if\f[R] (scriptAllowList.includes(input)) {
      \f[B]return\f[R] input; \f[I]// allow the script\f[R]
    }
    console.log(\(gaScript not in scriptAllowList: ${input}\(ga);
    \f[B]return\f[R] \(dq\(dq; \f[I]// Block the script\f[R]
  },
});
.EE
.PP
Next we\(cqll create the script element to which we will assign the
value and get a handle to the element.
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]script\f[R] id=\(dqel\(dq></\f[B]script\f[R]>
.EE
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// Get the script element we\(aqre injecting the code into\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] el = document.getElementById(\(dqel\(dq);
.EE
.PP
Then we use the \f[CR]policy\f[R] object to create a
\f[CR]trustedScriptURL\f[R] instance from the potentially unsafe input
string, and assign the result to the element:
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// The potentially malicious string\f[R]
\f[I]// We won\(aqt be including untrustedScriptURL in our scriptAllowList array\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] untrustedScriptURL = \(dqhttps://evil.example.com/naughty.js\(dq;

\f[I]// Create a TrustedScriptURL instance using the policy\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] trustedScriptURL = policy.createScriptURL(untrustedScriptURL);

\f[I]// Inject the TrustedScriptURL (which contains a trusted URL)\f[R]
el.src = trustedScriptURL;
.EE
.SS Reading the \f[CR]src\f[R] property
This example shows how you can read the \f[CR]src\f[R] property for the
two script elements below, assuming page URL is
\f[CR]https://example.com\f[R].
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]script\f[R] id=\(dqscript\-with\-src\(dq type=\(dqmodule\(dq src=\(dq/main.js\(dq></\f[B]script\f[R]>
<\f[B]script\f[R] id=\(dqscript\-without\-src\(dq type=\(dqmodule\(dq></\f[B]script\f[R]>
.EE
.PP
The code reads each of the script elements and logs the output of the
\f[CR]src\f[R] property.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] scriptWithSrc = document.getElementById(\(dqscript\-with\-src\(dq);
console.log(scriptWithSrc.src); \f[I]// Output: \(dqhttps://example.com/main.js\(dq\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] scriptWithoutSrc = document.getElementById(\(dqscript\-without\-src\(dq);
console.log(scriptWithoutSrc.src); \f[I]// Output: \(dq\(dq\f[R]
.EE
